<TEXT id="PaiwanCh2_020_THE STONE FAN" xml:lang="pwn" copyright="public domain" citation="Early, R. J., &amp; Whitehorn, J. (2003). One hundred Paiwan texts. Pacific Linguistics, Research School of Pacific and Asian Studies, The Australian National University." BibTeX_citation="@book{100paiwantexts, author = {Robert Early and John Whitehorn}, title = {One Hundred Paiwan Texts}, year = {2003}, publisher = {Pacific Linguistics, Research School of Pacific and Asian Studies, The Australian National University}}" source="sipaizan a qatsiɫay (Tjakuvukuvuɫ village, p.193)" dialect="Southern">
    <S id="020S1">
        <FORM kindOf="original">ka sitsuayan ka mangtjengtjez a masi naqemizing ti Salakats, izua sipaizan a qatsiɫay, a sikipaipaiz ni Salakats.</FORM>
        <PHON kindOf="original">ka siʦuajan ka maŋcəŋcəz a masi naqəmiziŋ ti saɭakaʦ, izua sipaizan a qaʦiʎaj, a sikipaipaiz ni saɭakaʦ.</PHON>
        <FORM kindOf="standard">ka sicuayan ka mangtjengtjez a masi naqemizing ti Salakac, izua sipaizan a qaciljay, a sikipaipaiz ni Salakac.</FORM>
        <PHON kindOf="standard">ka siʦuajan ka maŋʦəŋʦəz a masi naqəmiziŋ ti saɣakaʦ, izua sipaizan a qaʦiʎaj, a sikipaipaiz ni saɣakaʦ.</PHON>
        <TRANSL xml:lang="eng">Once upon a time when Sakalats had just come from land he had won(?), there was a stone fan which Sakalats used to fan himself.</TRANSL>
